07306nam a22018495i 9781400847358DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20131999nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008473587 a10.1515/97814008473582doi  a(DE-B1597)528125  a(OCoLC)842903511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a111.852231 aScarry, Elaine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Beauty and Being Just /cElaine Scarry. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (144 p.) :b7 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPART ONE. On Beauty and Being Wrong -- tPART TWO. On Beauty and Being Fair -- tNOTES -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHave we become beauty-blind? For two decades or more in the humanities, various political arguments have been put forward against beauty: that it distracts us from more important issues; that it is the handmaiden of privilege; and that it masks political interests. In On Beauty and Being Just Elaine Scarry not only defends beauty from the political arguments against it but also argues that beauty does indeed press us toward a greater concern for justice. Taking inspiration from writers and thinkers as diverse as Homer, Plato, Marcel Proust, Simone Weil, and Iris Murdoch as well as her own experiences, Scarry offers up an elegant, passionate manifesto for the revival of beauty in our intellectual work as well as our homes, museums, and classrooms. Scarry argues that our responses to beauty are perceptual events of profound significance for the individual and for society. Presenting us with a rare and exceptional opportunity to witness fairness, beauty assists us in our attention to justice. The beautiful object renders fairness, an abstract concept, concrete by making it directly available to our sensory perceptions. With its direct appeal to the senses, beauty stops us, transfixes us, fills us with a "surfeit of aliveness." In so doing, it takes the individual away from the center of his or her self-preoccupation and thus prompts a distribution of attention outward toward others and, ultimately, she contends, toward ethical fairness. Scarry, author of the landmark The Body in Pain and one of our bravest and most creative thinkers, offers us here philosophical critique written with clarity and conviction as well as a passionate plea that we change the way we think about beauty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAesthetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aA Dictionary of the English Language.  aAdjective.  aAlbertus Magnus.  aAll things.  aAlternative model.  aAmartya Sen.  aAnalogy.  aAristotle.  aBanishing.  aBeholder (Dungeons & Dragons).  aBenjamin Jowett.  aCalculation.  aCertainty.  aDeliberation.  aDionysus.  aDivine Comedy.  aEdition (book).  aEmbarrassment.  aEmily Dickinson.  aEncomium.  aEqual footing.  aEric Partridge.  aEtymological dictionary.  aEtymology.  aEuripides.  aFiligree.  aFragility.  aGenerosity.  aGenre.  aGood and evil.  aGreat Unity.  aGreat power.  aHarvard University Press.  aIllustration.  aImmanuel Kant.  aIris Murdoch.  aIrony.  aJohn Donne.  aJohn Keats.  aJohn Rawls.  aLa Vita Nuova.  aLecture.  aLifesaving.  aLoeb.  aMathematical proof.  aMathematician.  aModern English.  aNeoclassicism.  aNicomachean Ethics.  aNobility.  aObservations on the Feeling of the Beautiful and Sublime.  aOde to a Nightingale.  aOf Education.  aOn Beauty.  aOn the Aesthetic Education of Man.  aPalinode.  aParticle physics.  aP